Maybe a fisheye lens is a bit too much for a birdhouse.
You never learn from your mistakes.
I should have known better, since I already built one with a "normal" lens before.
I will write more about it over the weekend once I've installed the second one.
Let's just say the birds will have a better internet connection than I did in 2015.
At least that's the plan.
The box, which already has a nest in it, uses up a lot of WLAN data.
With the other one, it's a bit more difficult for it to go online.
Okay, I hung up the new birdhouse today. This is how it looks at its new location in the garden.
But let's go back a bit. No one asks: „What exactly is inside?“
At the top is one of these ESP32 camera boards with a camera featuring a fisheye lens and an IR-LED that I took from a Raspberry Pi camera.
The reason for the strange shape of this plastic box is the swivel side panel of the birdhouse. I bought it like that and couldn't change it, so I had to build around it.
Since there's no electricity in the garden, the whole thing is powered by a solar panel and a 2600 mAh 18650 cell.
I didn't photograph the cell or the charger, but here's a picture of the panel.
Inside the gray box hanging on the side of the birdhouse is the battery.
When it's charged, I get about 4 hours of runtime.
I'd call that a feature. So the birds also get some privacy.
At first, I wasn't sure if the internet in our garden would be sufficient for this setup. The old access points I replaced last fall wouldn't have been enough.
But the new ones cover this area very well.
It's almost a shame, because I had planned to install a TP-Link cpe210 on the roof and aim it downward into the garden.
Maybe I'll do that later, if/when I set up more camera-equipped birdhouses. Especially in areas that are further away from the house, I probably need that.
The camera is offline now, and I don't know why. It turned off just an hour after sunset.
Perhaps the battery didn't charge for three hours before sunset because there wasn't enough light.
Or maybe less than half a day was not enough to fully charge the battery.
I guess I'll have to wait and see what happens tomorrow.
I don't have telemetry for the battery. I might have to change that in the future.
In general, a few more sensors would be a good thing, I think.
And maybe a battery that at least theoretically is able to keep the thing running all night.
Ah yes, and another lens.
Fisheye is quite over the top.
But I'm already looking for parts on Digikey so I can build my own board for that purpose.
Or maybe not. We'll see.
And it's still offline.
Great.
According to the actual solar panels on the house, we only have about 90 minutes of proper sunlight.
Let's wait another hour or two to see what happens – or maybe not.
Still offline.
It's never easy.
It turned out that on the USB-C breakout board I used to connect the charger, the 5 V and GND were swapped on the silkscreen.
I swapped the cables and now the charging indicator is lit up.
The ESP didn't go online immediately. Let's wait a few minutes.
An hour has passed and it's still offline.
It looks like it's restarting and triggering a Tasmota reset function.
I think the panel is just not good enough. I've now ordered a larger one and hope that works.
Check out what I found in my workshop.
A 24-V panel. Unfortunately, the sun is already so low (and partially obscured by a tree), that the value practically drops to zero as soon as I turn on the device.
I'll probably have to wait until tomorrow to see if it's sufficient for this setup or if I need the better panel I ordered.
According to Amazon, I bought this panel in 2021 and it is supposed to deliver 12 V at a maximum of 1.2 A.
So either something is wrong with the panel or with my multimeter, or the data has been changed.
Good news!
You have changed the data and the ones I have are wrong.
The old one and also the new listing title call it a 12 V 10-W panel.
That's why I never delete old emails.
Oh look! The thing went online again for about half a minute around an hour ago.
Maybe the panel just charged the battery long enough for 38 seconds of runtime. For that, it only took a little more than two hours.
Ratet mal: Heute ist es bewölkt. Ich bin mir daher nicht sicher, ob das (wahrscheinlich kaputte) Solarpanel es schafft, überhaupt genug Strom zu erzeugen.
Mal abwarten.
Update: Ich habe das neue Panel installiert und jetzt scheint es zu funktionieren.
Es könnte immer noch ausgehen, sobald die Sonne untergeht, aber geben wir ihm eine Chance.
Funfact: Ich verwende die Ping-Integration in Home Assistant, um zu sehen, ob es online ist oder nicht.
The average connection time is 102 ms. Not particularly good, but also not incredibly bad.
